[Event "West Michigan Chess Championships: Fuller - Brooks"]
[Date "2019.10.29"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "B01"]
[Opening "Scandinavian Defense: Modern Variation"]
[StudyName "West Michigan Chess Championships"]
[ChapterName "Fuller - Brooks"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/Pte6Bci0/lmODX5SE"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/DrHack"]
[UTCDate "2019.10.29"]
[UTCTime "13:34:21"]

1. e4 d5 { The Scandinavian defense AKA the doughnut opening. The center has been cut out. } 2. exd5 Nf6 3. Nf3 Bg4 { Black attempts to develop rapidly in the hope that he can make wrestle the initiative early. GM Baskaran (2740) tried this in 2017 with disastrous results. } 4. Bc4 { If white hopes to gain an edge, he might try Bb5+. } (4. Bb5+ { Now black has an uncomfortable choice. He can gambit by c6 or Block his queen out of the game with a bishop or knight move which wrecks his idea of an early initiative. }) 4... Nxd5 5. Nc3 e6 6. Qe2 Be7 { White retains his development lead and the game is about as it should be. =/=
Consider this alternative - } 7. Bxd5 exd5 8. Qb5+ Nd7 9. Qxd5 c6 10. Qe4 Nf6 11. Qe2 O-O 12. O-O Re8 { Black has done well in this past series of moves. The key to an open center is piece control of those squares - which means pieces need to play into the game. Black has wrestled the lead in development from white by forcing the white queen to play around the board. } 13. d3 Bd6 { White can retain equality only by keeping equal in development and central control. He might try Ne4 so the queen can continue to be active from e2. } 14. Qd1 (14. Ne4) 14... Re5 15. h3 Rh5 { White wins by playing a calm defense. } 16. Ne4 (16. hxg4 Nxg4 17. g3 { This is an intuitive defense - count the number of defenders around the white king vs the number of attackers. Black does not have a local majority big enough to win. White will defend with Ne4, and by bringing a rook to h1. } { [%csl Gc3,Gf3,Gf1] }) 16... Bxh3 17. Bg5 Bg4 { In order to defend, white must bring new pieces to the king's side or trade black's attacking pieces. c3 may fit into that plan somehow, but it is not direct. Probably Qd2 or Qe2 was necessary. } 18. Re1 Bh2+ 19. Kf1 h6 20. Bxf6 gxf6 21. c3 (21. Qd2 Bxf3 22. gxf3 { The text seemed to avoid this variation. Is it so bad? White has good chances. }) 21... Bf4 22. Ng3 Bxg3 23. fxg3 { Tactics stem from undefended and under-defended pieces and pawns. I spot b2 and g3. Also, the king's best escape is f2 ;). } 23... Qd5 (23... Qb6 $19 { Any move to save the b2 pawn loses to Rh1+ followed by Re8+ } 24. d4 Qxb2 { +1 to black }) 24. Kg1 Rf5 25. Re4 h5 26. Qe2 Rd8 { The last series of moves was a quality build of the attack by black and perfect defense by white. } 27. d4 Qd6 28. Qf2 Kg7 29. Rae1 Rd7 { Tactics stem from undefended and under-defended pieces. a2 and d3 } 30. R1e3 c5 31. Qe1 Bxf3 32. gxf3 cxd4 33. Rxd4 Rd5 34. Red3 Qb6 35. Qf2 Rxd4 36. cxd4 Rd5 (36... Qa6 37. Ra3 Qc4 $17 38. Rxa7 Rxd4 { with a threat Qc1+ and Rd2 pinning the queen and king. This threat is unable to be defended from here. } 39. Kg2 Qd5) 37. Qd2 Qe6 38. Kg2 Qf5 39. Qe3 Qd7 40. b3 Qc6 41. f4 Rxd4+ 42. Kg1 Rxd3 43. Qxd3 Qc1+ 44. Kh2 Qb2+ 45. Kh3 Qxa2 46. Qf3 Qb1 47. Qxb7 Qf1+ 48. Qg2 Qxg2+ 49. Kxg2 Kg6 50. Kh3 f5 51. b4 a6 52. Kh4 f6 53. Kh3 Kh6 54. Kg2 Kg6 55. Kf3 Kf7 56. Ke3 Ke7 57. Kd3 Kd7 58. Kc3 Kc7 59. Kb3 Kb7 60. Ka3 Ka7 { 1/2 - 1/2 } *


